    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, but we're pretty constrained on resources since it's an embedded system, so I can't exactly run a massive profiler like Valgrind and eat up all the remaining memory. Could you suggest some more lightweight methods? maybe something like manual instrumentation or using static analysis tools to catch it before we deploy?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "For resource-constrained environments, manual instrumentation is often the most practical approach. You can wrap your standard memory allocation functions (`malloc`/`free` or `new`/`delete`) with lightweight wrappers that only track the *call stack* and *size* of each allocation. This stack trace logging needs to be minimal—perhaps just recording the return address or a unique ID—to avoid significant overhead. If you have a stable toolchain, static analysis tools can sometimes flag potential unmanaged resources, but the runtime tracking via instrumentation will offer the definitive proof of a leak in your long-running process.",
      "source": "target",
