    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i've tried a few lightweight wrappers but it's still taking forever to find the culprit. the leak is so small and slow that it's almost impossible to trace manually. it feels like this thing is just hiding in the background, popping up occasionally and then disappearing before i can catch it in the logs. any ideas on how to catch something that intermittent or elusive?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When the leak is small and intermittent, you need a change in how you observe the system, not just how you track memory. Instead of logging every allocation, try periodically taking a \"snapshot\" of the heap usage at fixed intervals, say every 30 minutes. Compare these snapshots to see exactly how much memory increased between measurement points, which narrows down the time window for the leak. Furthermore, if you can isolate the system into discrete operational states, run targeted tests for each state to see if the leak only occurs during a specific routine.",
      "source": "target",
